fields.physical_description:
Unbound portfolio of 35 posters in various media with front and back cover
[Cover] Brown card cover printed in yellow with publication title on the front and a list of artists and recipients on the back
[poster] Silhouette image of a rose with lettering printed in black on one side of an A3 sheet of white paper in portrait format
[poster] Photocopy on both sides of an A3 sheet of white paper.
Front: phonetic diagram and extract of a text on variants of laughter, portrait format.
Back: two facing pages of text from a book/chapter/article on contagious laughter, lanscape format.
[poster] Photographic portrait of a man printed in blue and black with abstract designs superimposed on the face, printed on one side of A3 white paper, portrait format.
[poster] Image showing black line drawing of three irregular interlocking circles of different sizes, lettered underneath in blue: Past, Present, Future. Printed on one side of A3 cream paper, portrait format.
[poster] Montage of drawings and text, photocopied in black on one side of an A3 sheet of white paper, landscape format.
[poster] Montage of imagess and text, photocopied in black on one side of an A3 sheet of white paper, portrait format.
[poster] Digitally manipulated image of a person in a clown costume (throwing a dart?), printed in black on one side of a sheet of A3 white paper, landscape format.
[poster] Abstract composition in black, red, blue, purple and orange on sheet of A3 white paper
[poster] Black and white image of an axe with the word "IF" on the shaft of the axe and the word "THEN" stencilled across the image, on an A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] Image of "pig tanker" printed in black with shadow stencilled in gold, legend printed in black within the image, "THE CABIN BEYOND MADE A GREAT BLACK MARK FOR THEY HAD BURNED ITS ROOF TO MAKE IT MORE POETIC..............", on A3 sheet of white clay paper (portrait format).
[poster] The words "PURE IMMANENCE" in cream letterpress on A3 sheet of white paper (landscape format)
[poster] A3 portion of artist's wallpaper with abstract pattern in black, pink, orange, grey and yellow, (landscape format). Pasted on the back a sheet of A4 white paper with an installation shot of the wallpaper in an exhibition at the Düsseldorf Kunstverein and the text of correspondence between Andrew (Hunt?) and the artist (portrait format).
[poster] Photographically-derived black and white image of a standing stone in a landscape. Superimposed on the image: the words "MILITANT BOURGEOIS" in white capital letters with the letter I replaced by musical notes hand-coloured in pink gouache and "an existential retreat" in black handwritten lower-case. A2 white paper (landscape format).
[poster] The words "HELLO, MAY I MISREPRESENT YOU?" lettered in black capitals, upper half of the image. Hand-applied abstract marks in masking tape and red and yellow acrylic over all. On A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] Mock up of front page of a newspaper with pictures and bodies of type represented by abstract forms resembling imaginary urban landscapes with elements of fantastic architecture. Printed in dark grey on pale grey paper (portrait format).
[poster] Background image combining scanned-in detail of a Morrocan banknote (top half) and Mars  bar wrapper (bottom half). Legend superimposed over the image reads "MOROCCO$ GROSS NATIONAL PRODUCT EQUALS FAMILY FORTUNE OF Mars (customised version of the Mars logo)" . On A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] Column of words and photographic images of hand gestures or sign language down the centre of the sheet: 
corxsn / whatever (in italics) / corectn / wotev (italics) / corechun / wtva (italics) / correction / (2 images of street hand gesture for "whatever"[?]) / correction / (image of British Sign Language sign for the letter W [?]). Printed in black on A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] Image consists of the words "not forms and colours" in dark lower-case lettering and some dark specks occupying upper area of the sheet, intentionally very slightly mis-registered to create barely visible "bleed" of cyan, magenta and yellow around the edges of the letters and specks making them seem almost to vibrate on the page. The words "after Joseph Kosuth after Douglas Huebler after Lawrence Weiner... Artforum, Vol.36, No.3, p.16" printed in grey near  bottom edge of sheet. A3 cream paper (portrait format).
[poster] Sheet of A4 white paper (portrait format) with the word "right" printed in black letters about 2/3 of the way down the left-hand edge of the paper and scribbled out and replaced with the word "right" hand-written in pencil. In the same place on the right-hand edge of the sheet the word "left" treated in the same way.
[poster] Texted proposing a demonstration and speculating about its possible course and outcome, printed in black art deco-style lettering, each paragraph being set in successively smaller type, the whole text contained in a black border, on a sheet of A3 green paper (portrait format).
[poster] Evening Standard newsvendor's poster for Monday's edition with the headline "£100, 000 HUMAN CLONES". Printed in blue, black and orange on white paper (portrait fromat) folded in four.
[poster] Abstract form stencilled in black on A3 sheet of white cartridge paper (portrait format) torn from a spiral-bound pad.
[poster] Words in handwritten style "rock and roll and let go" superimposed over background composition of figures under a shower or sprinkler. The words "ITCHY PARK III 2006 LIQUID ECONOMICS" lettered within the background compostion. Printed in orange and black on yellow A3 paper (portrait format).
[poster] B&W photocopy of a drawing with coffee rings (?) on A3 sheet of white paper (landscape format).
[poster] Surreal composition of three gold feathers floating in space, the largest being ridden by a female nude. On a sheet of A3 white paper (portrait format).
[poster] Laser print in black on A3 sheet of cream watercolour paper (portrait format) of pen and ink drawing of a fan-like arrangement of strips numbered one to one hundred and fifty, strip number 56 is hand-coloured with turquoise gouache.
[poster] Advertisement for Hard Mag (self-published artists' magazine) printed in colour on an A3 sheet of white glossy card (landscape format). The style of the ad references B-movie posters and the main image is a montage of movie stills - principally terrified reaction shots - with billowing smoke and a digitally-manipulated image of Tate Modern at Bankside.
[poster] B&W photographically-sourced image of a Lynn Chadwick sculpture of two seated figures. A pink pawprint has been added to the left eye orbit of one of the figures. On A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] A3 sheet of blue card (portrait format) with white card CD sleeve mounted on the sheet and containing a CD (see E.52:32-2007).
[poster] 3-track audio CD printed on one side with photographically-sourced image of sky and treetops, lettered in white within the inage with the title and a list of names (of contributing artists?)
[poster] B&W photocopy of an ink drawing of knives and handwritten legend "When I find out your name all of the knives will be thrown" on A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] B&W photocopy of a photographic image of theatrical actors (a man and a woman) in character, the word "inferno" is handwritten across the centre of the image in acrylic paint, A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format).
[poster] B&W photocopy on sheet of A4 white paper (landscape format) showing back view of the head of a young man with a Microsoft manual.
[poster] B&W photocopy on A4 sheet of white paper (landscape format) showing head of a young man holding a Microsoft manual in his left hand and smiling.
[Cover] Information about the publication (title, alphabetical list of contributing artists and titles of their contributions, other credits, acknowledgements and instructions) lettered in yellow on A3 sheet of brown card (portrait format). Edition number stamped in black within the design.
[poster] B&W photocopy of page 11 from the Metro newspaper for Monday, April 18th 2005, featuring an article about the artist vandalising cars. On A3 sheet of white paper (portrait format.

fields.public_access_description:
Slimvolume was set up in 2000 to provide an open space for artists to expand their practice within a collective curatorial framework. This is the fifth 'Poster Publication' in a projected series (one a year) and it contains work by artists from several countries, and is a mix of established artists and new names. The Museum also has the 2002, 2003 and 2004 publications. 

The publication is not bound. It is conceived both as a conventional portfolio and also as a readymade exhibition. The prints are protected by card covers, the one at the back listing the contents of the set and giving publication details. The works themselves are simultaneously prints, posters and artists' multiples. 

An important part of the project is its method of distribution. The edition is allocated to people chosen by the participating artists and the organisers. The recipients are free to exhibit or distribute all or parts of the set, or to keep it intact. A list of those receiving the 2004 publication is included. Slimvolume is an example of the many ways in which artists (and print publishers) are working outside the conventional gallery system, exploiting new strategies to publish, promote and exhibit their work.
